"I Find It Hard To Write A Scene Though I Can See It In My Head"
This is incredibly common. And it has nothing to do with talent.

Here's what's happening:

Your brain is a cinema. You see the lighting, the expressions, the cuts, the music, the silence between words. It's all there — vivid, emotional, alive.

Then you sit down to write.

And the cinema in your head meets the white page. And the white page feels like a wall. Because a movie is not words. A movie is images in time. Writing is capturing those images with a net made of sentences.

The secret that nobody tells you:

You don't have to write the scene the way you see it.

You just have to write something that points toward it.

A single line. A piece of dialogue. A gesture. A description of light on a face. Then another line. Then another.

The scene doesn't arrive fully formed. It accumulates.

