Option B: The Broadcast Model (Timelines as Radio Stations)
The core idea:

Reality is not a simulation. It's a continuous broadcast — like radio, like television, like frequencies in the air all around us.

Most people are born locked into one frequency — the one they can perceive. They live their whole lives thinking that's all there is.

But there are infinite frequencies. Each frequency is a different timeline. Every timeline is real. They're all happening simultaneously, right now, in the same space.

You just can't see them. Because you're tuned to your channel.

The Bleed: Where frequencies overlap. Static. You can hear echoes of other channels here.

Awakening: Learning to adjust your perception. To hear other frequencies. To see other timelines.

The Maintainers: People who know about the other frequencies and actively try to keep everyone locked into one channel. Not because they're evil. Because they believe opening all channels at once would shatter the human mind.

HIM's goal: His girlfriend died on his frequency. But somewhere on another frequency — another channel — she's still alive. He's not trying to bring her back. He's trying to change channels. To leave his frequency and join hers.

The cafe scene (the ending): He succeeds. He finds her frequency. She's sitting by the window. She waves. He waves. The screen blacks. "Pianoman" plays.

The tragedy (implied): He's not on his frequency anymore. Everyone he knew — his family, his friends, the people who loved him on his original channel — they're gone to him. He can't go back. He chose her. And he's at peace with that.

How it's different from The Matrix: In The Matrix, the "real world" is a ruined wasteland and the simulation is a lie. In Option B, every frequency is real. His original frequency wasn't a lie. It was just one version of reality. He didn't "escape." He switched.

The Merged Version: Broadcast + Performance
The core idea:

Take Option B (infinite frequencies, each a real timeline).

Now add one more layer:

The broadcasts aren't random. They're scripted.

Long ago — so long that nobody remembers — someone wrote a performance. A story. A script that dictates how reality unfolds on each frequency. Different frequencies have different outcomes (she lives, she dies), but they all follow the same structural rules.

Over time, the performance became autonomous. It no longer needs a writer. It plays itself. The Maintainers aren't running the broadcast — they're just keeping the performance from glitching.

The Bleed: Where the performance breaks down. Where you can see the script. Where the actors (people) realize they're in a play.

Awakening: Realizing you're a character in a performance that's been running so long that everyone forgot it was written.

The Gray Character (voice-turned-physical): Someone who found the original script — or fragments of it — and wants to rewrite it. To change the rules. To become the new author.

HIM's goal: He doesn't want to rewrite the script. He doesn't care about the performance. He just wants to find the one frequency where the script says she lives. And then stay there. Even if that means becoming a character in a play he doesn't understand, forever.

The cafe scene (the ending): Same as Option B. He finds her frequency. She's alive. They see each other. The screen blacks.

But the merged version adds a final beat (optional): After the black screen, a single line of text appears. Something like: "End of performance. Frequency preserved." Or nothing at all. Just the implication that he's happy inside a script he'll never escape.

How it's different from Option B: Option B is about navigation (finding the right channel). The merged version is about acceptance (knowing you're in a script and not caring, because she's there).

